attributes.title: Reasoning about durations
attributes.description: Few experiments have examined how people reason about durative relations, e.g., during. Such relations pose challenges to present theories of reasoning, but many researchers argue that people simulate a mental timeline when they think about sequences of events. A recent theory posits that to mentally simulate durative relations, reasoners do not represent all of the time points across which an event might endure. Instead, they construct discrete tokens that stand in place of the beginnings and endings of those events. The theory predicts that when reasoners need to build multiple simulations to solve a reasoning problem, they should be more prone to error. Three experiments tested the theory by providing participants sets of premises describing durative relations; participants judged whether the sets were consistent or inconsistent. The results validated the model theory's prediction. We conclude by situating the results in recent work on the neurocognitive mechanisms that underlie temporal thinking.

attributes.title: Fake News: Prior Exposure, Information presentation format and need for cognition.

q1.value: Fake News: Heuristic of recognition, information presentation format and Need for Cognition

q3.value: Fake news are a good source of mass manipulation. The innovation of the study will be to highlight the belief in fake news correlated with the need for cognition and the type of stimulus from the previous exposure phase.

q4.value:
People will have a higher rate in believing fake news if they were prior exposed to the image that is presented in the article, as compared to a condition where they have not been  exposed to any content in the article.

People will have a higher rate in believing fake news if they were prior exposed to the title that is presented in the article, as compared to a condition where they have not been  exposed to any content in the article.

People will have a higher rate in believing fake news if they were prior exposed to the title and picture that is presented in the article, as compared to a condition where they have not been  exposed to any content in the article.

Also, we expect to find differences in people's credibility in fake news, depending on the type of content they were previously exposed to, although we do not have enough information to anticipate which type of previously seen information (picture, title, or picture+ title) will weigh the most.

People's need for cognition is related to their credibility in fake news.

attributes.title: Narcissism, Emotion Recognition Accuracy, and Mind Reading Motivation

q1.value: Narcissism, Emotion Recognition Accuracy, and Mind Reading Motivation

q3.value:
Research from our lab and others suggests that grandiose narcissism (GN) is negatively correlated with emotion recognition (ER). Our lab recently completed data collection for a study that tested correlations between GN and ER (data collected between October 15-December 4, 2019; N = 291). GN was measured with the Five Factor Narcissism Inventory (FFNI) and ER was measured with the Reading the Mind in the Eyes Test (RMET) and the Geneva Emotion Recognition Test (GERT). This study was exploratory in nature as previous research is rather unclear regarding how GN correlates with behavioral measures of ER. The results of this study suggest that GN correlates negatively with both measures of ER: RMET r(289) = -.24, p < .001; GERT r(289) = -.26, p < .001. 

The goal of this preregistered study is to (1) replicate the negative correlations between GN and ER and (2) test a followup hypothesis that mind-reading motivation (MRM) explains the negative association between GN and ER. In this study, MRM will be measured with a recently developed measure called the Mind Reading Motivation Scale (MRMS). Specifically, we will test whether the correlation between GN and ER is significantly (p < .05) confounded (non-causally mediated) by MRM. That is, whether grandiose narcissists are generally unmotivated to read the minds of others and this is why they perform poorly on tests of emotion recognition.

q4.value:
Hypothesis 1: GN will be negatively correlated with MRM and ER.

Hypothesis 2: MRM will be positively correlated with ER.

Hypothesis 3: The correlation between GN and ER will be significantly (p < .05) explained by MRM. This hypothesis will be tested using confound analysis. Confound analysis (CA) is mathematically identical to mediation analysis (MA), however, unlike MA, CA is not causal in nature. There is no need to assume that GN causes MRM, which would be necessary to establish causal mediation. Rather, MRM is assumed to be a trait-level characteristic of GN that confounds (i.e., explains/accounts for) the association between GN and ER. In other words, individuals with high levels of GN are also hypothesized to have low levels of MRM, which is hypothesized to explain why individuals with GN perform poorly on measures of ER.

q5.value: Observational Study - Data is collected from study subjects that are not randomly assigned to a treatment. This includes surveys, “natural experiments,” and regression discontinuity designs.

value: No blinding is involved in this study.

question.value: This is a cross-sectional study. All participants will complete all measures of GN, MRM, and ER.

q9.value: There are no experimental manipulations in this study.

q10.value: Registration prior to creation of data

q11.value: The data for this preregistered study do not exist. The plan is to collect this data during the Spring 2020 semester.

question.value: Participants will be undergraduate students enrolled in introductory psychology courses at the University of South Alabama. All participants will be recruited through the subject pool (using SONA Systems subject pool software) and will be issued participation credit in exchange for completing the study.

q13.value: A minimum sample of 200 participants will be collected for this study.

q14.value:
The focal effect is a confound effect (a non-causal mediation effect). Sample size to achieve a minimum of .80 power was estimated using Schoemann, Boulton, and Short's (2017) R Shiny app, which uses Monte Carlo simulation to estimate power to detect confound effects at different sample sizes: https://schoemanna.shinyapps.io/mc_power_med/.
The app requires input of zero-order correlations and standard deviations between GN, MRM, and ER. Values for GN and ER are based on data collected during a previous study by our lab that included these variables (N = 291).

GN: FFNI SD = 20.71.

ER: RMET SD = 3.57; GERT SD = 8.69.

Correlation between FFNI and RMET: r = -.24.

Correlation between FFNI and GERT: r = -.26.

The SD for MRM (measured using the MRMS) was estimated based on Study 1 of Carpenter, Green, and Vacharkulksemsuk’s (2016) scale development paper (SD = 0.79). Likewise, the correlation between MRM and ER was based on the same study and paper. Carpenter et al. did not directly assess ER, but they did assess interpersonal perception using the Interpersonal Perception Test-15. Although clearly not the same thing, we thought that interpersonal perception was the closest approximation of ER available in the extant literature to base our estimated correlation (r = .32). 

Finally, we did not have a solid empirical basis on which to estimate the correlation between GN and MRM. The Carpenter et al. (2016) did report correlations between MRM and Big 5 personality traits: neuroticism (r = .08), openness (r = .45), conscientiousness (r = .13), agreeableness (r = .34), extraversion (r = .05). GN, especially when measured with the FFNI, is significantly correlated positively with extraversion (r = .20), negatively with openness (r = -.16), negatively with agreeableness (-.53), and negatively with conscientiousness (r = -.24). It is non-significantly correlated with neuroticism (r = .10). (These values were taken from the Sherman et al., 2015, FFNI scale development paper; Table 3, Undergraduate Sample.) Given these correlations--especially those involving agreeableness and openness, we believed a reasonable and conservative estimate of the correlation between GN and MRM is, r = .20.

When these values are entered for power analyses using either the RMET or GERT at the outcome variables, the results are nearly identical. They look as below (ranges indicate that estimated sample size differed between RMET and GERT):

80% power: N = 190-200.

85% power: N = 220.

90% power: N = 260.

95% power: N = 310-320.

In summary, this power analysis suggests that we need to attain a sample of approximately 200 participants to reach a minimally acceptable power of 80%.

q15.value:
We will collect data until one of the following conditions are met:

(1) The university semester ends and we have at least 200 participants in the sample, or
(2) We have 320 participants in the sample.

Using this stopping rule, we will have an estimated 80% to 95% power by the end of the study.

question.value: This is an observational study.

GN will be measured with the grandiose narcissism subscale of the Five Factor Narcissism Inventory. ER will be measured with two tests: (1) Reading the Mind in the Eyes Test and (2) the Geneva Emotion Recognition Test. MRM will be measured with the Mind Reading Motivation Scale. 

The only planned demographic covariate is biological sex. This will be used to control for possible sex differences in GN and ER. Additionally, the amount of time participants take to complete the GERT will also be recorded (specifically, the amount of time that elapses between the moment each video ends and the moment participants click the submit button to submit their response). This is being recorded to control for the possibility that participants will high GN will rush through the GERT and get low scores because of lack of effort. To be clear, neither one of these covariates affected the results of the previous study. Biological sex and time to complete the GERT were both unrelated to GERT performance (r = .05 and .07, respectively). Time to complete the GERT was also unrelated to GN (r = .01). Biological sex was related to GN (females scored lower than males; r = -.16, p = .006).

The principal analyses will use the measures in the raw (non-combined) form. It is possible that secondary analyses might be conducted on latent variables representing the constructs of GN, MRM, and ER. If so, these results are expected to mirror those attained using the variables in their raw form.

Bivariate correlations (Pearson product moment correlations) will be used to test whether (1) GN is negatively correlated with ER, (2) GN is negatively correlated with MRM, and (3) MRM is positively correlated with ER. All tests involving ER will be done twice; once using the GERT and again using the RMET. 

These tests will be followed up with a confound analysis (i.e., non-causal mediation analysis) to test--we will use mediation language to avoid confusion-- whether the indirect effect of GN on ER through MRM is significant (p < .05). This test will be conducted once for each measure of ER (i.e., GERT and RMET).

q21.value: All tests will be evaluated using p-values. Tests producing p-values of less than .05 will be described as significant. Significant tests that are in the hypothesized direction will be described as supporting the hypotheses. All tests will be 2-tailed. Therefore, if a test produces a significant result that is opposite of that hypothesized, we will describe it as that (rather than describing as a null).

q22.value: Data will not be excluded unless it is missing (see missing data section).

q23.value: Missing data is expected to be minimal (participants will be asked to go back and complete any missed items before proceeding to the next section of the study). Participants with missing data on ER (either measure), GN, or MRM will be excluded using listwise deletion. If this results in an unacceptable amount (>10%) of exclusions, other missing data techniques (e.g., imputation, FIML) will be considered. Regardless, the results from participants with complete data for ER, GN, and MRM will be reported alongside results attained using missing data techniques.

attributes.title: Signs of Safety Evaluation
attributes.description: Evaluation of Signs of Safety based on a difference-in-difference approach.

q1.value: Signs of Safety English Innovation Programme Wave 2 - Evaluation Extension

q2.value: Eva Schoenwald, Vicky Clayton, Michael Sanders

q3.value:
A research project by What Works for Children's Social Care (https://whatworks-csc.org.uk/).

Background

Signs of Safety (S of S) is an approach to child protection that was developed in Australia in the 1990s. S of S is now widely used in children’s social care in England (used in its ‘pure’ form or in ‘some form’ in least 91 local authorities), despite little to no evidence around the effects of using this model. The Department for Education (DfE) supported Munro, Turnell and Murphy (MTM) Consulting, under Wave 1 of the Education Innovation Programme, to work with 10 local authorities in England to implement S of S. The 10 pilot local authorities were evaluated by Health Social Care Workforce Research Unit - King's College London (HSCWRU). HSCWRU is currently conducting further evaluation of S of S with 8 of the same local authorities plus an additional local authority in Wave 2 of the Innovation Programme. What Works for Children’s Social Care (WWCSC) is complementing the HSCWRU’s evaluation in this phase through conducting a difference-in-difference analysis. The aim of this analysis is to obtain quasi-causal estimates of the effect of S of S on:

•	The duration of assessments
•	The likelihood of an initial child protection conference
•	The likelihood of cases designated as 'no further action' (NFA)to be re-referred
•	The likelihood of cases to be re-referred and result in a child protection plan (CPP) 
•	The likelihood of a child or young person becoming looked after (CLA)
•	The share of kinship care vs non-kinship care 

Quasi-causal estimates are useful to get to an accurate picture of the effect of S of S and so can help decision-makers in local authorities to make decisions on whether or not to invest in S of S. This work builds on WWCSC’s systematic review of S of S focusing on reducing entry to care.

q4.value:
Although there are a range of possible outcomes that could be assessed, we focus on only two primary outcomes to avoid problems associated with multiple comparisons. These two outcome variables were selected on the basis that they have shown promise in the Wave 1 evaluation and Wave 2 interim findings, and in discussions with HSCWRU. 
Our hypotheses are as follows:
•	S of S reduces the duration of assessments. 
•	S of S reduces the likelihood of an initial child protection conference. 
Based on discussions with MTM to better understand S of S's theory of change, in addition to hypotheses regarding the primary outcomes, we will test three secondary hypotheses, namely: 
•	S of S reduces the rate of re-referrals of cases that have previously been assessed as no further action (NFA). 
•	S of S affects the rate of re-referrals that lead to a child protection plan (CPP) or to a child becoming looked after (CLA). 
•	S of S increases the rate of kinship care and reduces the rate of non-kinship care for children who are looked after.

q5.value: Observational Study - Data is collected from study subjects that are not randomly assigned to a treatment. This includes surveys, “natural experiments,” and regression discontinuity designs.

value: No blinding is involved in this study.

q7.value: This research does not involve allocation to treatment, and so blinding is not relevant.

question.value:
The design of the analysis is a difference-in-difference (DiD) design with repeated measurements over time. There is no randomisation into treatment and control group. Control groups are determined through matching on pre-treatment trends in outcomes. 
The unit of analysis is at an individual level to optimise the power to detect an effect within the constraints of the project.

q9.value: This research does not involve allocation to treatment, and so randomisation is not relevant.

q10.value: Registration prior to accessing the data

q11.value: The analysts have not had access to the individual-level data prior to registration. The data is being made available by the Department for Education (via a standard application process) and will be accessed via the Office for National Statistics Secure Research Service (SRS).

question.value:
We collect data via an application to the Department for Education. We request data on the local authorities that have implemented Signs of Safety under the DfE's Innovation Programme and on comparator local authorities identified through matching. We will only use data on individuals that have been in contact with children's services through assessments, CIN or CPP plans or through being in care. 

We expect to receive the data by February 2020 and will then conduct individual-level matching between children in treatment and control groups. 

Please see the attached document for full details on our data collection procedures.

data.name: Data collection procedures S o S.docx

extra.selectedFileName: Data collection procedures S o S.docx

q13.value: Up to 710,000 children from 9 treatment local authorities and up to 18 control local authorities.

q14.value: We have not included power calculations for this analysis because there are too many assumptions that we would need to make for the power calculations to be useful. Furthermore, because of the retrospective nature of the DiD analysis, sample size is constrained more by the practicalities of data access than for other projects.

q15.value: Sample size will be determined by the number of individuals that meet the criteria for the population in our treatment groups. There is no need for a stopping rule for our treatment group. We will match these individuals with individuals in comparator groups via Coarsened Extract Matching.

question.value: N/A - no manipulation of variables.

Outcome measures 
To answer research question 1, the outcome measure is: duration of assessment (days). We only consider assessments that have started and finished outside of the embedding period (we anticipate SofS will need a period of time after implementation to be fully functional and to allow new practices to be fully embedded - we thus exclude this embedding period from our analysis). 
To answer research question 2, the outcome measure is: the likelihood of an initial child protection conference (ICPC) (0-1). We only consider the likelihood of an ICPC for children that have already been assessed and whose case is designated as open. 

To answer research question 3, the outcome measure is: the likelihood of a case that received an NFA to be re-referred within a 6-month window (0-1). 
To answer research question 4, the outcome measure is: the likelihood of a case that are re-referred within a 6-month window and lead to a CP plan or the child becoming looked after (0-1). 
To answer research question 5, the outcome measure is: the likelihood of looked after children and children who ceased to be looked after that to be cared for through kinship care (0-1).

Covariates
In order to increase the precision of our estimates, we include the following individual-level and local authority covariates (where they are available). We do not include individual-level 
fixed effects because the same child is unlikely to, for example, both be assessed and have an initial child protection conference multiple times in the time period of interest.

•	The date when the referral was made (included as binary indicators: 0=Usual, 1= the day after a bank holiday or the 5 days before school holidays) 
•	How many previous plans a child has had (integer) 
•	The main need which the episode is taking care of. (included as a categorical variable: 0 = Not stated, 1 = Abuse or neglect, 2 = Child's disability/illness, 3 = Parental Disability/illness, 4 = Family in acute stress, 5 = Family dysfunction, 6 = Socially unacceptable, 7 = Low income, 8 = Absent parenting, 9 = Cases other than Children in Need) for children in need
•	Latest category of abuse. (included as a categorical variable: 1= Neglect, 2= Physical abuse, 3= Sexual abuse, 4= Emotional abuse, 0=Multiple/ Not recommended)

Analysis plan
Primary Analysis:
As our approach to identifying causal impacts is a DiD approach, we match local authorities based on the extent to which they meet the assumptions for that identification strategy. In particular, this will involve matching on the trends of the outcome measures over the last few years, rather than the levels of those outcome measures. Matches are identified on the basis of similarity (the inverse of the Euclidean distance).

Prior to analysis, each local authority will be matched with two candidate control local authorities based on trends in our outcomes of interest. This matching having been completed, we will estimate the effect of the intervention on the outcomes of interest via a regression (linear for continuous dependent variables and logistic for binary dependent variables) that includes an indicator for treatment or control (LAs that are implementing Signs of Safety or not) , an indicator for before or after treatment (whether LAs implementing Signs of Safety have implemented it at time t) and an interaction term between the two. The coefficient on the interaction term is the coefficient of interest.

We control for time trends through year dummies and include individual and local authority level characteristics as controls. Standard errors are clustered at the local authority level.

We include data for t-1 and from t+e until the current year where e is the time taken to reach a steady state to allow the evaluation of the programme to start when teams understand and have become accustomed to new ways of working (the embedding period). The time taken to reach a steady state comes from triangulation of qualitative work conducted by Mary Baginsky and a survey of the pilot LAs at a SofS leadership day. For some local authorities this is a gap of up to 36 months from when SofS started until it reached a steady state. We investigate whether the estimated timing of the steady state affects the treatment effect in the sensitivity analysis.

DiD involves multiple observations of the control and treatment groups over time. This can create serial correlation where errors in one period transfer to another. Serial correlation can be a particularly important issue in the DiD context because of the inclusion of fairly long time series, dependent variables which are commonly used  are typically highly positively serially correlated, and the treatment variable changes little within a local authority over time. Serial correlation underestimates the standard errors, meaning that we have too much confidence in the result, and we get a higher rate of false positives. We check for serial correlation using the Durbin-Watson test. We consider there to be serial correlation if the test statistic is outside of the range of 1.5 - 2.5. Serial correlation is partially taken care of when clustering at the local authority level. To counteract individual-level serial correlation, we also try a multilevel model with standard errors clustered at both the individual and the local authority level and consider whether the multilevel model produces a statistically different and practically different estimate of the treatment effect to the treatment effect estimated from the primary analysis  (where we take practically different to be 20% above or below). 

Secondary Analysis:
Additional subgroup analyses 
We further investigate whether the effect of SofS is more pronounced within certain subgroups (subject to availability of the data). We investigate whether local authorities which self-report to have SofS embedded well have different treatment effects. We categorise local authorities based on a composite of their self-reported profiling scores. The score came from the  “Profiling survey” conducted by HSCWRU as of the beginning of Wave 2: 0-4, 5-6, 7-8, 9-10 where 0 is “not at all embedded” and 10 is “fully embedded”. 
We also categorise local authorities based on their Ofsted ratings and MTM’s scoring of the quality of delivery and conduct subgroup analyses for each of these categories. We run separate regressions for each of these categories and plot the coefficient on the DiD variable against the profiling score to visually inspect whether the subgroups have different treatment effects. 

Channels
We test whether SofS influences the duration of assessments by increasing the number of same day assessments by including a dummy for same day assessment in the regression and reporting whether it is significant.

Practice models
We recognise that there may be overlap between the SofS model and two other popular practice models, Restorative Justice and Reclaiming Social Work. If the mechanisms through which the three practice models are expected to affect outcomes are the same, comparing the pilot SofS local authorities to local authorities using Restorative Justice or Reclaiming Social Work would bias downwards any potential effect. We ask the comparator local authorities whether they use either practice model. In this analysis, the original Signs of Safety indicator becomes a three-level indicator of whether the local authority received SofS (the base category), a similar practice model (Restorative Justice and Reclaiming Social Work), or neither.


We will further validate our results through sensitivity analyses. Here we will use placebo tests which recode comparator and treatment local authorities and we explore the effect of time-varying treatment effects on the outcomes, given that the treatment effect might be sensitive to the timing chosen for the treatment to be fully embedded and implemented.

registration_responses.q2: Eva Schoenwald, Vicky Clayton, Michael Sanders
registration_responses.q3:
A research project by What Works for Children's Social Care (https://whatworks-csc.org.uk/).

Background

Signs of Safety (S of S) is an approach to child protection that was developed in Australia in the 1990s. S of S is now widely used in children’s social care in England (used in its ‘pure’ form or in ‘some form’ in least 91 local authorities), despite little to no evidence around the effects of using this model. The Department for Education (DfE) supported Munro, Turnell and Murphy (MTM) Consulting, under Wave 1 of the Education Innovation Programme, to work with 10 local authorities in England to implement S of S. The 10 pilot local authorities were evaluated by Health Social Care Workforce Research Unit - King's College London (HSCWRU). HSCWRU is currently conducting further evaluation of S of S with 8 of the same local authorities plus an additional local authority in Wave 2 of the Innovation Programme. What Works for Children’s Social Care (WWCSC) is complementing the HSCWRU’s evaluation in this phase through conducting a difference-in-difference analysis. The aim of this analysis is to obtain quasi-causal estimates of the effect of S of S on:

•	The duration of assessments
•	The likelihood of an initial child protection conference
•	The likelihood of cases designated as 'no further action' (NFA)to be re-referred
•	The likelihood of cases to be re-referred and result in a child protection plan (CPP) 
•	The likelihood of a child or young person becoming looked after (CLA)
•	The share of kinship care vs non-kinship care 

Quasi-causal estimates are useful to get to an accurate picture of the effect of S of S and so can help decision-makers in local authorities to make decisions on whether or not to invest in S of S. This work builds on WWCSC’s systematic review of S of S focusing on reducing entry to care.
registration_responses.q4:
Although there are a range of possible outcomes that could be assessed, we focus on only two primary outcomes to avoid problems associated with multiple comparisons. These two outcome variables were selected on the basis that they have shown promise in the Wave 1 evaluation and Wave 2 interim findings, and in discussions with HSCWRU. 
Our hypotheses are as follows:
•	S of S reduces the duration of assessments. 
•	S of S reduces the likelihood of an initial child protection conference. 
Based on discussions with MTM to better understand S of S's theory of change, in addition to hypotheses regarding the primary outcomes, we will test three secondary hypotheses, namely: 
•	S of S reduces the rate of re-referrals of cases that have previously been assessed as no further action (NFA). 
•	S of S affects the rate of re-referrals that lead to a child protection plan (CPP) or to a child becoming looked after (CLA). 
•	S of S increases the rate of kinship care and reduces the rate of non-kinship care for children who are looked after.

attributes.title: How perceived credibility and perceived opinion climate mediate people's willingness to share

q1.value: Perceived credibility, SoS, and willingness to share

q3.value: Social media has outpaced print newspapers and magazines as an important news source. Meanwhile, people get news from a bunch of intermediaries on social media such as friends and family, celebrities, official accounts of news media, etc. As friends and celebrities are two main intermediaries on social media, this study aims to test from these two intermediaries, how people's perceived credibility of news influences their willingness to share the news, as well as how people's perceived majority opinion influences people's willingness to share.

q4.value:
H1: News shared by celebrities as compared to news shared by friends will lead to higher willingness to share.
H2a:Perceptions of opinion climate will mediate willingness to share such that (a) news shared by celebrities will be perceived as more consistent with major opinion climate as compared to news share by friends, which will in turn (b) increase people's willingness to share the news.
H2b: Perceptions of credibility will mediate willingness to share such that (a) news shared by celebrities will be perceived as more credible as compared news shared by friends, which will in turn (b) increase people's willingness to share the news.

q5.value: Experiment - A researcher randomly assigns treatments to study subjects, this includes field or lab experiments. This is also known as an intervention experiment and includes randomized controlled trials.

value: For studies that involve human subjects, they will not know the treatment group to which they have been assigned.

question.value:
This study has a between subject design with 1 factor (intermediary) with 2 levels (friends, celebrities). Two sets of questionnaires will be administered. To reduce, if not remove, any systematic influences from participants’ self-report of personal issue involvement, and attitude toward LGBTQ issues, data on these factors were collected as the study’s control variables in the first questionnaire. 
Participants will then randomly assigned to one of two intermediary scenarios in the second questionnaire. They will be presented a mock Weibo page, with a piece of LGBTQ issue news shared by one of two kinds of intermediaries. 
The two scenarios consisted of the same news source from “People’s News”（”人民日报”）, which is one of the most credible and official news outlet in China. Participants were given instructions that said, “You have received this news on Weibo from [specific intermediary variable tested]”. Participants were either told that the news were shared by (a) a person of their close network or (b) a well-known celebrity in China.

q10.value: Registration prior to creation of data

question.value: Paticipants will be recruited by www.wjx.cn, a Chinese crowdsourcing website which can conduct web-based human-subjects experiments.

q13.value: My target sample size is 172 participants. I will attempt to recruit up to 200 people.

q14.value: I used G*Power to conduct a power analysis. My goal was to obtain 0.90 power to detect a medium effect size of 0.25 at the standard 0.05 alpha error probability.

question.value:
The intermediary will be manipulated. The two levels of this varible are (a) a person of their close network (b) a well-known celebrity in China.
Manipulation checks will be conducted to check (a) how close is the participant to the person of their network and (b) how popular is the celebrity in China.

The dependent varible will be people's willingness to share. This varible will be measured on a 5- point scale ranging from 1 = extremely unlikely to share to 5 = extremely likely to share.
The mediating varibles will be: (a) perceived news credibility (b) perceived majority opinion.
I will use one-way ANOVA analysis for the group comparison. For the observations in each group, I will use SEM (Standard Error of the Mean) analysis.

The two scenarios consisted of the same news source from “People’s News”（”人民日报”）, which is one of the most credible and official news outlet in China. Participants were given instructions that said, “You have received this news on Weibo from [specific intermediary variable tested]”. Participants were either told that the news were shared by (a) a person of their close network or (b) a well-known celebrity in China.

The intermediary will be manipulated. The two levels of this varible are (a) a person of their close network (b) a well-known celebrity in China.
Manipulation checks will be conducted to check (a) how close is the participant to the person of their network and (b) how popular is the celebrity in China.
registration_responses.q17.question:
The dependent varible will be people's willingness to share. This varible will be measured on a 5- point scale ranging from 1 = extremely unlikely to share to 5 = extremely likely to share.
The mediating varibles will be: (a) perceived news credibility (b) perceived majority opinion.
